16 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
17 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
18 Article – Family Law
19 5–701.
20 (a) Except as otherwise provided in § 5–705.1 of this subtitle, in this subtitle the
21 following words have the meanings indicated.
22 (b) (1) “Abuse” means:
23 (i) the physical or mental injury of a child under circumstances that
24 indicate that the child’s health or welfare is harmed or at substantial risk of being harmed
25 by:
26 1. a parent;
27 2. a household member or family member;
28 3. a person who has permanent or temporary care or custody
29 of the child;
30 4. a person who has responsibility for supervision of the
31 child; or
32 5. a person who, because of the person’s position or
33 occupation, exercises authority over the child;

HOUSE BILL 1389 3
1 (ii) sexual abuse of a child, whether physical injuries are sustained
2 or not; or
3 (iii) labor trafficking of a child by any individual.
4 (2) “ABUSE” INCLUDES FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION, AS DEFINED
5 IN § 20–601 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
6 (3) “Abuse” does not include the physical injury of a child by accidental
7 means.
8 5–704.
9 (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, including any law on privileged
10 communications, each health practitioner, police officer, educator, or human service
11 worker, acting in a professional capacity in this State who has reason to believe that a child
12 has been subjected to abuse or neglect:
13 (1) shall notify the local department or the appropriate law enforcement
14 agency; and
15 (2) if acting as a staff member of a hospital, public health agency, child care
16 institution, juvenile detention center, school, or similar institution, shall immediately
17 notify and give all information required by this section to the head of the institution or the
18 designee of the head.
19 (b) (1) An individual who notifies the appropriate authorities under subsection
20 (a) of this section shall make:
21 (i) an oral report, by telephone or direct communication, as soon as
22 possible to the local department or appropriate law enforcement agency; and
23 (ii) a written report:
24 1. to the local department not later than 48 hours after the
25 contact, examination, attention, or treatment that caused the individual to believe that the
26 child had been subjected to abuse or neglect; and
27 2. with a copy to the local State’s Attorney.
28 (2) (i) An agency to which an oral report of suspected abuse or neglect
29 is made under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall immediately notify the other agency.
30 (ii) This paragraph does not prohibit a local department and an
31 appropriate law enforcement agency from agreeing to cooperative arrangements.

4 HOUSE BILL 1389
1 (c) Insofar as is reasonably possible, an individual who makes a report under this
2 section shall include in the report the following information:
3 (1) the name, age, and home address of the child;
4 (2) the name and home address of the child’s parent or other person who is
5 responsible for the child’s care;
6 (3) the whereabouts of the child;
7 (4) the nature and extent of the abuse or neglect of the child, including any
8 evidence or information available to the reporter concerning possible previous instances of
9 abuse or neglect; and
10 (5) any other information that would help to determine:
11 (i) the cause of the suspected abuse or neglect; and
12 (ii) the identity of any individual responsible for the abuse or neglect.
13 Article – Health – General
14 20–601.
15 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION” MEANS A PROCEDURE
16 PERFORMED FOR NONMEDICAL REASONS THAT INVOLVES PARTIAL OR TOTAL
17 REMOVAL OF OR OTHER INJURY TO THE EXTERNAL FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING:
18 (1) A CLITORIDECTOMY OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL OF THE
19 CLITORIS, PREPUCE, OR CLITORAL HOOD;
20 (2) EXCISION OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL, WITH OR
21 WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS, OF THE LABIA MINORA, WITH OR WITHOUT
22 REMOVAL OF THE LABIA MAJORA;
23 (3) INFIBULATION OR THE NARROWING OF THE VAGINAL OPENING,
24 WITH OR WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS; OR
25 (4) ANY OTHER PROCEDURE THAT IS HARMFUL TO THE EXTERNAL
26 FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING PRICKING, PIERCING, INCISING, SCRAPING, OR
27 CAUTERIZING THE GENITAL AREA.
28 [20–601.] 20–602.

HOUSE BILL 1389 5
1 (a) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a person [who
2 circumcises, excises, or infibulates the whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora
3 or clitoris of an individual who is under the age of 18 years is guilty of] MAY NOT:
4 (1) KNOWINGLY PERFORM, ATTEMPT TO PERFORM, OR CONSPIRE TO
5 PERFORM female genital mutilation ON AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18
6 YEARS; OR
7 (2) TRANSPORT AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18 YEARS
8 OUT OF THE STATE FOR THE PURPOSE OF PERFORMING OR FACILITATING THE
9 PERFORMANCE OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON THE INDIVIDUAL.
10 (b) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a parent, guardian,
11 or other individual is guilty of female genital mutilation if the individual:
12 (1) Is legally responsible and charged with the care or custody of a child
13 under the age of 18 years; and
14 (2) Knowingly consents to [the circumcision, excision, or infibulation of the
15 whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora or clitoris of] THE PERFORMANCE
16 OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON the child.
17 [20–602.] 20–603.
18 (a) A surgical operation is not a violation of this subtitle if the operation is
19 necessary to the health of the individual on whom it is performed and is performed by a
20 person licensed in the State as a medical practitioner.
21 (b) In determining whether an operation is necessary to the health of the
22 individual, no account may be taken of the belief on the part of any individual that the
23 operation is required as a matter of custom or ritual.
24 [20–603.] 20–604.
25 (A) A person who violates the provisions of this subtitle is guilty of a felony and
26 on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding [5] 10 years or a fine not exceeding
27 [$5,000] $10,000 or both.
28 (B) IF AN INDIVIDUAL WHO HOLDS A LICENSE ISSUED UNDER THE HEALTH
29 OCCUPATIONS ARTICLE IS CONVICTED OF, ENTERS A PLEA OF GUILTY OR OF NOLO
30 CONTENDERE FOR, OR RECEIVES PROBATION BEFORE JUDGMENT FOR A VIOLATION
31 OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE APPLICABLE HEALTH OCCUPATIONS BOARD SHALL REVOKE
32 THE LICENSE OF THE INDIVIDUAL.
33 20–605.

6 HOUSE BILL 1389
1 (A) A VICTIM OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION PERFORMED IN VIOLATION
2 OF THIS SUBTITLE MAY FILE AN ACTION IN THE CIRCUIT COURT IN THE COUNTY IN
3 WHICH THE VIOLATION OCCURRED OR THE VICTIM RESIDES.
4 (B) IF THE COURT FINDS THAT A PERSON VIOLATED THIS SUBTITLE, THE
5 COURT MAY AWARD THE PLAINTIFF:
6 (1) ACTUAL DAMAGES;
7 (2) COMPENSATORY DAMAGES;
8 (3) PUNITIVE DAMAGES;
9 (4) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES, COURT COSTS, AND LITIGATION
10 EXPENSES, INCLUDING EXPERT WITNESS FEES AND EXPENSES; AND
11 (5) ANY OTHER APPROPRIATE RELIEF.
12 (C) AN ACTION BROUGHT UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL
13 BE FILED THE LATER OF:
14 (1) NOT MORE THAN 10 YEARS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH THE
15 VIOLATION OCCURRED; OR
16 (2) THE DATE ON WHICH THE VICTIM OF THE VIOLATION REACHES 28
17 YEARS OF AGE.
18 20–606.
19 (A) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2027, THE
20 DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE SOCIAL SERVICES ADMINISTRATION,
21 STATE AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES, AND OTHER APPROPRIATE
22 GOVERNMENT AGENCIES AND PUBLIC AND PRIVATE ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL
23 SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF
24 THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, CONTAINING DE–IDENTIFIED AND
25 DISAGGREGATED DATA ON THE NUMBER OF:
26 (1) REPORTS OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION SUBMITTED IN
27 ACCORDANCE WITH § 5–704 OF THE FAMILY LAW ARTICLE;
28 (2) INDIVIDUALS PROSECUTED FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;

HOUSE BILL 1389 7
1 (3) INDIVIDUALS CONVICTED OF A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;
2 (4) CIVIL ACTIONS FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SUBTITLE; AND
3 (5) CIVIL ACTIONS UNDER THIS SUBTITLE IN WHICH A JUDGMENT
4 WAS ENTERED, WHETHER BY SETTLEMENT OR ADJUDICATION.
5 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAKE THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER
6 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC.
7 20–607.
8 THE DEPARTMENT, IN COLLABORATION WITH COMMUNITY–BASED
9 ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL:
10 (1) DEVELOP AND PUBLISH CULTURALLY AND LINGUISTICALLY
11 APPROPRIATE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS ON FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION,
12 INCLUDING:
13 (I) THE SIGNS THAT AN INDIVIDUAL HAS BEEN SUBJECTED TO
14 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION;
15 (II) THE PHYSICAL AND MENTAL HEALTH RISKS CAUSED BY
16 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION; AND
17 (III) THE CRIMINAL PENALTIES FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS
18 SUBTITLE; AND
19 (2) DISTRIBUTE THE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS DESCRIBED UNDER
20 ITEM (1) OF THIS SECTION TO:
21 (I) HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS;
22 (II) LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES;
23 (III) SCHOOLS;
24 (IV) THE PUBLIC; AND
25 (V) ANY OTHER PROFESSIONAL OR COMMUNITY–BASED
26 ORGANIZATIONS THAT MAY WORK OR INTERACT WITH INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE AT
27 RISK OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION.

8 HOUSE BILL 1389
1 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
2 October 1, 2026.

